messages.text:
hey 'Me', hope you're doing fine

1. YLD rebalancing is the process where YIELD App refills the treasury, by buying YLD off of the open market to pay for rewards / for sale within the app via the swap / etc, currently this is as close to the treasury "address" we have available, I put it in quotes because internally it is a bit more complex than a single address, which is why we put it on our stats page.

2. Yes, all YLD rewards are paid with the treasury.

3. Max supply is 300m, circ supply is how much it's currently circulating, you can refer to the graph below for more info on YLD emission

messages.text: To me, something like Yield can fly, if they remove the need for those basic competencies. It should be as easy as using an online bank account. Think how many people will use this if they buy btc/eth/USDC with fiat then just withdraw profits whenever they want, without having to worry about contract addresses and "enough eth for gas" and whatever else. It should be about mainstream adoption.
I understand your point of view

I nearly lost $100k of tokens because I'd copied and pasted a project contract address into Metamask to add as a custom token, then went to transfer tokens from one wallet to another. I forgot that the project contract address was still on my clipboard and I'd pasted it as my "send" address. Luckily I check what I'm doing 3 or 4 times before any transaction but its easy to make mistakes!
I'm in the UK and would love it if Yield could get FCA approval as a fiat ramp. It would be unbeatable. "Buy bitcoin or eth with your debit card and earn at least 10% interest".
ok, thx
You can have this (10%) with EUR and GBP at coinloan, almost as easy as you describe.

I get your point and understand the risk.  The cost of carelessness can be high.  I also understand your analysis that ease of use and de-risking of the transfer will improve adoption.  Checks for like block chain and confirmation messages are useful tools to achieve that and other platforms have implemented that as well, as mentioned above.  Frankly I think the greater benefit, more generally for us individuals, is derived from building the competence and self reliance that comes from the almost brutal impact of carelessness,  although would agree it is not Yield's job to develop this in its customers.  These quality are increasingly necessary and increasingly rare.   I would argue that the ability to do hard, risky and necessary things will stand you in good stead in life.   So I don't disagree with you, and I know that your intent is to help the community, my challenge to people is: rather than thinking about making things easier, make yourself better.  (and not talking about you per se Alex but 'us' in general).  People can do what they like, just my opinion.

text.text: Users receive interest on their investment and bonuses on their tokens in three ways:

text:
1. Your investment in USDT/USDC/ETH earns 10% APY, paid in USDT/USDC/ETH.

2. Users receive up to a 10% APY boost on their investment by holding YLD tokens in the app, paid in YLD. Users without YLD tokens still receive a 2% APY boost, earned in YLD.

3. YLD tokens also generate up to a 10% annualized holding reward, paid daily in YLD.

Please note that total APY will depend on the level of your investment, the token price of YLD and the amount of YLD you hold. Token information, reward tiers and APY calculator

Hey Anthony, I gladly share my reasoning behind it. But I would first like to react to a few misunderstandings in your reply. First, I do not think I have expressed any critisism towards Yieldapp. I only shared my personal thoughts on Cefi platforms in general. And like in any business environment, there are economic mechanisms that no company, be it in the traditional or in the crypto world, can escape. In order to survive, it is all about size. Every starting company has to grow and battle its way up. If we get amazing apy's at Yieldapp, way higher then number 2 in the space, it is  because the company chooses to attract more customers that way. I would be naive to believe that Yieldapp is the only company that knows how to generate those yields, trust me, all the others are fishing in the same pools. And the bigger marketshare they get, the smaller apy's they will need to offer. One example: Tesla has the most expensive electric cars at the moment, with no "deals or bargains" whatsoever since a long time, simply because they are market leader atm. As we speak, there are amazing deals to be had with the electric models at Ford, Renault, Toyota and many more. Just the same battle of marketshare. Nothing wrong with that.
Secondly, I have never claimed that you or anyone at Yieldapp ever mentioned that rates are destined to go down, moreso then up. That is just my own believe.

It is Yield app's business choice to grow and get marketshare through massive apy's, that has to be respected. It is not because i personaly don't think it is the best and the only way to grow, that this strategy should not be respected. But luckily, in this part of the woods, we still live in a free world. It is important to express one's views, and i believe that not all contrary views can be regarded as fud. That would be a bit simple.

Since the start of this project, we've been saying that YIELD App strategy is not public, but it's always in DeFi. Some people discovered that we use Curve, which is not surprising as it can be read in the blockchain itself.

All information about the strategy is there in the FAQ since day one, Sterling. It is not a black box and it's readable.

How do you know that your deposited capital is still intact? 

How do you know the team wasn‚Äôt scammed or hacked and lost some funds?

How do you know they didn‚Äôt lose value betting the wrong way on price appreciation of one of the assets?

How can you know anything about anything? Without reporting you know nothing and that is all I want to point out and simply ask if this is how they plan to run the company forever or if the investors can expect some results in the future

You can read some of the CEO's thoughts about the sustainability, risk management and strategies that are being used here:

"We see DeFi as a sustainable industry built on solid fundamentals. We see 10% as sustainable long term and we can securely offer above this. On the first instance and within the current macro climate, we can generate Alpha through economies of scale. By aggregating capital and employing technology solutions to compliment the portfolio team, YIELD is in a position to profit from trading strategies that are not available to individual or market participants with insufficient capital reserves. 

Examples of this may include priority access to protocol testnets and in turn as a primary liquidity provider to new protocols in mainnet.
 
YIELD‚Äôs portfolio allocations are diversified across multiple strategies and trading opportunities; these can include automated funding rate arbitrage and asset disposals through our proprietary portfolio management system that is able to identify the highest yielding market opportunities and process these through YIELD‚Äôs internal risk analysis algorithms to generate instantaneous execution and transaction requests for digital approval (multi-sig) by our portfolio managers.
 
Outside of execution methodologies and tools, YIELD believes that DeFi as a nascent asset class is only at the starting point of a multi-year growth trajectory.  As with any new financial market innovation, it is inevitable that inefficiencies will be present; this is particularly amplified in the context of cryptocurrencies and the P2P nature of decentralized finance.
 
To that effect, it can be considered that the ‚ÄòRisk-Adjusted Rate of Return‚Äô, the trade-off between risk and expected returns or the risk premium that an investor demands for investment participation in decentralized financial instruments, will naturally be measured against other mature income generating financial instruments. We are seeing this today through the outsized returns (>1,000% APY) that can be achieved using complex liquidity mining strategies and re-hypothecation techniques.
 
We believe that our 10% APY will be sustainable in the long run due to these reasons, notwithstanding the inherent risk premium ascribed to cryptocurrency assets against a backdrop of perpetually low interest rates since the global financial crises, central bank fiscal loosening policies before and during the COVID-19 pandemic, and the dearth of high Income, low risk alternative assets classes available to non-sophisticated investors.
 
The minimum APY offered to YIELD users is nonetheless subject to change at the discretion of management and will be reviewed in line with broader market attributes and prevailing underlying benchmarks."

Its Cefi/Defi
Hybrid lol
Ok ty...
It's CeFi in the sense that funds are not held by the users, but it is DeFi in the sense that we make use of several DeFi protocols
What's centralized and what's decentralized about Yield ?

Centralized - users do not have the keys to their funds once they deposit to YIELD App, similar to how exchanges work.

Decentralized - we make use of the blockchain and different smart contract protocols to earn the yields we offer to our users

text: For more specific info on which protocols we make use of, I'd suggest giving a read to our whitepaper, it goes into depth in this and other topics related to the platform, here:

A little excerpt from page 4 might help with your question:

"...Decentralized Finance: the next big thing in FinTech is already hereIn recent years, decentralized finance (DeFi) has emerged as the most exciting innovation in FinTech. DeFi solutions rely on smart contracts and blockchain technology to deliver financial instruments that are mutualized, peer-to-peer, permissionless, and fully automated. These can be assembled into even more complex solutions to further drive rapid innovation.DeFi solutions currently fall into a few prominent categories. These include:

‚Ä¢ Prediction Markets (Gnosis and Augur)
‚Ä¢ Collateralized Lending (Aave)
‚Ä¢ Collateralized Stable Assets (DAI)
‚Ä¢ Automated Market Makers (Uniswap, Balancer)
‚Ä¢ Derivatives (Synthetix and Opyn)
‚Ä¢ Smart Contract Insurance (Nexus Mutual)
‚Ä¢ Permissionless Aggregators (Zapper)
‚Ä¢ Non-Fungible Tokens (NFTs) are also now used to generate value from digital collectibles, gaming tokens, digital art, and other goods and services in a permissionless manner."

I'll give it a go...

Eip 1559 will nog change anything for us. Fees will be the same. They only spike less fast and will be more predictable. So small transactions on uniswap and minting EFT's etc still will be costly.

That said... The biggest change seems to be that the miners get way less of the fees. 

The fees are burned.  And the miners get a small miner fee/tip.

Some say this will be like 3x a BTC halving because the miners can't sell Eth anymore. Or not much. Might be good for price. Also the fees that burn when volume is high might or might not do something for the price.

Hash rate will probably go down. Only fans/cool people will mine. Validators get a mining tip... Safety of the network will go down (a little only) because of this.

This paves the way to 2.0. that will probably follow quicker than we expect. That's my guess.

If 2.0 is successful... I think we might see Ethereum do very well...  Perhaps a flippening of BTC (not soon but eventually), because the climate change narrative is very strong all over the world (except in the USA where about 50% seem to not care/understand), and people are not cool with the energy consumption of pow, and stake is the future...

Ps. Rumor has it that it will be delayed.
